[normal]Summary [bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]11.1.
[normal] 
[normal]Place-based finance that provides areas with greater control over their tax, spending and borrowing
[normal],
[normal] allowing a stronger focus on the needs of both local people and the local economy;
[normal]11.2.
[normal] 
[normal]Fair, transparent and certain distribution of local gov
[normal]ernment finance led by local government, which could be extended to the funding for other public services;
[normal]11.3.
[normal] 
[normal]Five year funding settlements for local public services
[normal],
[normal] providing certainty and the basis for greater service integration, early intervention and in
[normal]vestment in growth;
[normal]11.4.
[normal] 
[normal]Scrapping the Barnett Formula for allocating funding to the devolved nations, and investing in preventative public services that reduce demand on
[normal],
[normal] more expensive
[normal],
[normal] acute services.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The case for fiscal devolution[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Taking de[bold]cisions closer to [bold]local people[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Geography and governance[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Laying the fo[bold]undations for fiscal devolution[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]29.1.
[normal] 
[normal]Giving local government full control over council tax rates and discounts and removing requirements for referendums;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]29.2.
[normal] 
[normal]The full localisation of business 
[normal]rates which
[normal],
[normal] if it took place
[normal],
[normal] would mean local government could be self-funding in 2018-19 when the totality of business rates and council tax exceeds the current funding projections;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]29.3.
[normal] 
[normal]Removing the centrally set Housing Revenue Account borrowing cap
[normal],
[normal] allowing councils to build homes to full capacity. We estimate this could result in up to an additional 60,000 new homes over the next five years. Furthermore reforming the classification of council borrowing for housing would bring the UK into line with 
[normal]Europe in the way it classifies this kind of borrowing and end the preoccupation with where the borrowing sits for accounting purposes
[normal],
[normal] rather than the value attained for the investment
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]33.1.
[normal] 
[normal]e
[normal]mployment 
[normal]support where the re-tender of the Work Programme in 2016 provides an opportunity for co-commissioning between local government and the Department of Work and Pensions or a transfer of commissioning responsibility;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]33.2.
[normal] 
[normal]a transfer of responsibility for vocatio
[normal]nal skills
[normal],
[normal] so that provision can be shaped to fit the needs of the local economy and skills mismatches 
[normal]can be 
[normal]corrected, such as training 94,000 people in hair and beauty for 18,000 vacancies nationally
[normal];
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]33.3.
[normal] 
[normal]a
[normal] new local approach to engaging young people age
[normal]d between 16 and 25 years in work and learning that substitutes more successful local programmes for the plethora of less successful national programmes;
[normal] and
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]33.4.
[normal] 
[normal]local decisions about the investment in roads
[normal],
[normal] bring
[normal]ing
[normal] the Highways Agency under local control.
